Project Background

Does the way information is presented to us influence risky choice?

24 adults participated in an fMRI study where they were asked to make a series of choices between different lotteries In one condition, participants learned via description were shown visual representations of the lotteries. In the other, partcipants learned from experience, and were allowed to sample from the two lotteries before choosing which they would ultimately like play.

  • 4 blocks (2 description, 2 experience)
  • 36 choices per condition
  • 72 trials/subject

To get a sense of what our data is going to look like, lets check out the codebook.

Data Cleaning

How many trials did participants miss?

sum(is.na(df$safeChoice))
## [1] 54

Uh oh! One of the choice types doesnt have similar expected value (one choice is mathematically superior to the other). Lets remove that from the dataset well use for our analyses, as well as the null repsonses.

df.s <- subset(df, !is.na(resp) & ProbNumber != 'MD3')

Does the way information is presented to us influence risky choice?

m1 <- glmer(safeChoice ~ (1|subj) + probFormat, family=binomial(), data=df.s)
stargazer(m1, type='text', covariate.labels=c('Information Condition'), dep.var.labels=c('Risky Choice (OR)'))

Lets visualize this model! Since were using a really simple model, we probably only need to look at a bar plot. But interpretting odds ratios for logistic regression isnt always intuitive. We can use the effects package to transform our beta values into predictive probabilties.

class(m1) <- 'lmerMod'
m1.estimates <- effect('probFormat', m1)
m1.estimates.df <- data.frame(m1.estimates)
m1.estimates.df
m1.estimates.df$probFormat <- ordered(m1.estimates.df$probFormat, 
                                      levels = c('dbdm', 'ebdm'),
                                      labels = c('Described', 'Experienced'))

g1 <- ggplot(m1.estimates.df, aes(x=probFormat, y=fit)) +
  geom_bar(stat='identity', position=position_dodge(), fill=wes_palette('FantasticFox1',n=2)) + 
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=lower, ymax=upper), width=.2, size=.25, position=position_dodge(.9)) +
  ylab('Likelihood of Choosing \nthe Risky Option') + xlab('Presentation Format') + 
  theme_minimal()
g1

What about a more complex model?

Does the valence of the rare option in the lottery impact the relationship between information condition and choice?

# first we have to code whether the rare outcome was favorable (positive relative to the common outcome),
# or unfavorable (negative relative to the common outcome)

# let's find the probably and monetary value of the frequent outcome
df.s$PFreq <- ifelse(df.s$P1_1 > .5, df.s$P1_1, df.s$P2_1)
df.s$OFreq <- ifelse(df.s$P1_1 > .5, df.s$O1_1, df.s$O2_1)

# probability and monetary value of the rare outcome
df.s$PRare <- ifelse(df.s$P1_1 < .5, df.s$P1_1, df.s$P2_1)
df.s$ORare <- ifelse(df.s$P1_1 < .5, df.s$O1_1, df.s$O2_1)

# if we have a .50.50 probability, let's list it as NA for now (it won't be included in our analyses)
df.s$ORare[df.s$PRare==.5|df.s$PFreq==.5] <- NA
df.s$OFreq[df.s$PRare==.5|df.s$PFreq==.5] <- NA
df.s$PRare[df.s$PRare==.5] <- NA
df.s$PFreq[df.s$PFreq==.5] <- NA

# coding whether the monetary value of the rare outcome is greater than the frequent outome
df.s$RareFav <- ifelse(df.s$ORare > df.s$OFreq, 1, 0) # here, zero could be anything (depends on Rare Fav)
df.s$RareFav <- factor(df.s$RareFav, levels=c(0,1), labels=c('Rare Unfavorable', 'Rare Favorable'))


# let's build our model
m2 <- glmer(safeChoice ~ (1|subj) + RareFav*probFormat, family=binomial(), data=df.s)
stargazer(m2, type='text', covariate.labels=c('Information Condition', 'Outcome Favorablility', 'Condition*Favorability'),
          dep.var.labels=c('Risky Choice (OR)'))

Now, we could visualize the model the same way, using ggplot2. But what if we want to emphasize the fact that the way information is presented and outcome favorability shift peoples choice behavior? This is where I prefer sjPlot.

plot_model(m2, type = "est",show.ci = TRUE, show.p=TRUE, show.values=TRUE, title="", 
           legend.title=c('Format'), axis.title=c('Odds Ratio'), 
           colors=wes_palette('Darjeeling1',n=1), vline.color='grey') + 
  theme_bw() + theme(plot.margin=margin(2,5,1,0,'cm'))

plot_model(m2, type='int', colors=wes_palette('Darjeeling1',n=2), title="", axis.title=c('Format', 'Liklihood of Choosing the Risky Option'), legend.title='Rare Outcome Favorability') + theme_bw() + theme(plot.margin=margin(2,1,2,1, 'cm'))

Does RT differ between our two information conditions?

Lets assume we are assessing this as an exploratory question. Ggstatsplot is great for performing analyses that are more exploratory since they provide you with so much information in a single graph!
